    {
      "id": "m5RYkWv33rzutMvsRJHFx",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1078.9075301713422,
      "y": 41094.40919892791,
      "width": 292.841796875,
      "height": 24.660156249999993,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bYD",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2101931685,
      "version": 329,
      "versionNonce": 2063506469,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772388285493,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Q What DNS uses TCP or UDP?",
      "fontSize": 19.728124999999995,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Q What DNS uses TCP or UDP?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "2xKO1C5QTbZlFE-4RLM5H",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1131.920967671342,
      "y": 40568.29591767791,
      "width": 1188,
      "height": 475,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bYE",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1493470699,
      "version": 1020,
      "versionNonce": 1290002053,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772388245036,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "When we are sending packet in between client and destination or between two systems, \n\none way is\nwe continuously send packets without making sure that receiver received or not. Like we know the\nreceiver address and we keep on sending. Lets say we need to send 1000 packets, we are not concerned\nabout whether the packet is receiver or not by receiver. From our side we have to send assuming\nthat the packet will be received, this is UDP.\nHence UDP will keep on sending at a bullet speed, without checking that packet received by Receiver\nor not.\nExample -> Gaming, Live Streaming, Television its all UDP, due to UDP sometime in Live\n            streaming voice breaks in between but it doesn't stop because it doesn't take care \n            packet is successfully reached or not otherwise in TCP if someone tells then we will \n            hear 1 minute later due to it make sure packet is delivered to destination.\n\nTCP -> in TCP every packet that we send, receiver will send a acknoledgement packet is received or\nnot, if some packets are not delievered then we will ressend the corresponding packets to make sure\nour complete transmission is done, Hence TCP make sure packet is reached destination with correspoding order\n    Example -> If we are sending file to someone due to if some packet is missing that file is of no use\n                    ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "When we are sending packet in between client and destination or between two systems, \n\none way is\nwe continuously send packets without making sure that receiver received or not. Like we know the\nreceiver address and we keep on sending. Lets say we need to send 1000 packets, we are not concerned\nabout whether the packet is receiver or not by receiver. From our side we have to send assuming\nthat the packet will be received, this is UDP.\nHence UDP will keep on sending at a bullet speed, without checking that packet received by Receiver\nor not.\nExample -> Gaming, Live Streaming, Television its all UDP, due to UDP sometime in Live\n            streaming voice breaks in between but it doesn't stop because it doesn't take care \n            packet is successfully reached or not otherwise in TCP if someone tells then we will \n            hear 1 minute later due to it make sure packet is delivered to destination.\n\nTCP -> in TCP every packet that we send, receiver will send a acknoledgement packet is received or\nnot, if some packets are not delievered then we will ressend the corresponding packets to make sure\nour complete transmission is done, Hence TCP make sure packet is reached destination with correspoding order\n    Example -> If we are sending file to someone due to if some packet is missing that file is of no use\n                    ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "oNDoIM1bm3vUwbin2GoVo",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1136.604561421342,
      "y": 41128.56154267791,
      "width": 847,
      "height": 75,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bYF",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 497381,
      "version": 128,
      "versionNonce": 2054109739,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772388805916,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "TCP make sense because we need IP address for sure. then why it is using UDP?\n\nWhat happens is in TCP(48 Minutes)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "TCP make sense because we need IP address for sure. then why it is using UDP?\n\nWhat happens is in TCP(48 Minutes)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
