    {
      "id": "DsSXzRwJYxZ-eUQLOAWAT",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1149.684639546342,
      "y": 41695.43458955291,
      "width": 1089,
      "height": 550,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bYR",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2078957354,
      "version": 1380,
      "versionNonce": 1550497526,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772540995004,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "lets say DNS uses TCP\n1 -> it will connect with Rounter 3 message (3 way handshake)\n2 -> Router will connect with DNS 3 message to make sure Router receives the query\n3 -> Between DNS and RNS 3 message\n4 -> 3 message from RNS to DNS\n5 -> 3 message between DNS to TLD\n6 -> 3 from TLD to DNS\n7 -> 3 for DNS to ANS\n8 -> 3 for ANS to DNS\n9 -> 3 from DNS to ROuter\n10 -> 3 for router to Client\n\nall these handashakes that are happening\n Will it make the system slow or not?\n    Yes it will slow and during accerssing website we can't expect things to be slow.\n\nSecond problem is due to so many message our DNS will be very busy and this DNS will be hit by\nall over the world, this has to be kept free. So that it can respond fast. For this purpose\nwe are doing it on UDP. Its okay if we are not receiving a response hit it again, becuase structure\nis very robust we will assume it suppose to be done in 1 go. So that is final structure and that is\nwhy in DNS we assume UDP. DNS uses UDP protocol. SInce in TCP for every new client DNS need to do \n3 way handshake.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "lets say DNS uses TCP\n1 -> it will connect with Rounter 3 message (3 way handshake)\n2 -> Router will connect with DNS 3 message to make sure Router receives the query\n3 -> Between DNS and RNS 3 message\n4 -> 3 message from RNS to DNS\n5 -> 3 message between DNS to TLD\n6 -> 3 from TLD to DNS\n7 -> 3 for DNS to ANS\n8 -> 3 for ANS to DNS\n9 -> 3 from DNS to ROuter\n10 -> 3 for router to Client\n\nall these handashakes that are happening\n Will it make the system slow or not?\n    Yes it will slow and during accerssing website we can't expect things to be slow.\n\nSecond problem is due to so many message our DNS will be very busy and this DNS will be hit by\nall over the world, this has to be kept free. So that it can respond fast. For this purpose\nwe are doing it on UDP. Its okay if we are not receiving a response hit it again, becuase structure\nis very robust we will assume it suppose to be done in 1 go. So that is final structure and that is\nwhy in DNS we assume UDP. DNS uses UDP protocol. SInce in TCP for every new client DNS need to do \n3 way handshake.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "_qAmN43VqDwdZFRGrWtux",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1064.961983296342,
      "y": 42387.46583955291,
      "width": 957,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
