    },
    {
      "id": "GV4b2AnSgr8h9d9MCizWj",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1134.309639546342,
      "y": 43634.51662080291,
      "width": 1155,
      "height": 800,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bZ0",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 5186422,
      "version": 3188,
      "versionNonce": 1314231658,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772563460829,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "One good thing that we know about each of these is that they have a IP address like IPA , IPB, IPC,\nand so on, Now when they have a IP, I just have to figure out at which IP my error is coming. Now this\nis very interesting example of  application development. we know data is sent via packets, Not all the\nIPs in the world are dynamic, Some IPs are suppose to be static to make sure our network run smoothly\nSo mostly at the server level all the Ips that we see are static only. Not all the IPs are dynamic, And\nthis network we are talking obout, this is not a regular network, this is the network between 2 companies\nand these 2 companies are trying to communicate with each other.\nNow we will talk about where the issue is lying or who is suppose to manage or handle the issue?\nIf this issue coming at my company end for example I got a airtel connection and other company got a jio\nconnection, now if the issue is in my side, so I will ask with my service provider that your one of the\nsystem is showing some issues please check that. If the issue is in their side, I am getting one of their\nISP, I will tell the company that please contact to your ISP, There is a issue that is coming and please\ncheck on this. So they will check with their ISP or they will check to their own system , own firewall, \nif I am able to cross my part which means we are getting issue in other company system or IP.\nSo we have to make sure where the issue is.\n    If we will see packet structure, developer has played game over here, what they started doing is \nthat they start noticing the packet and in packet there are multiple thing which are of different use.\n        version -> tells us version of IP address. Are we using IPV6 or IPV4.\n        headers length -> it tells us the length of header from version to options.\n        total length -> it tells us total length from version to data everything. Along with the\n                data packets and everything, How much is my total length of packet\n        data part -> it is the data that we are trying to send.\n        source ip -> we already discussed\n        destination ip -> we already discussed.\n        checksum -> it make sure that, the data we are sending is not altered in the way. if anything\n                change then our checksum and data will not match. it makes sure data reached\n                to the destination without any touch ups in between.\n                there is on very interesting part of packet which is called as TTL\n\n        TTL(Time to Live) -> It is basically added in a packet to make sure there are no network \n                    loops or data is not stuck in network forever.\n                What are Network loops -> to understand network loops",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "One good thing that we know about each of these is that they have a IP address like IPA , IPB, IPC,\nand so on, Now when they have a IP, I just have to figure out at which IP my error is coming. Now this\nis very interesting example of  application development. we know data is sent via packets, Not all the\nIPs in the world are dynamic, Some IPs are suppose to be static to make sure our network run smoothly\nSo mostly at the server level all the Ips that we see are static only. Not all the IPs are dynamic, And\nthis network we are talking obout, this is not a regular network, this is the network between 2 companies\nand these 2 companies are trying to communicate with each other.\nNow we will talk about where the issue is lying or who is suppose to manage or handle the issue?\nIf this issue coming at my company end for example I got a airtel connection and other company got a jio\nconnection, now if the issue is in my side, so I will ask with my service provider that your one of the\nsystem is showing some issues please check that. If the issue is in their side, I am getting one of their\nISP, I will tell the company that please contact to your ISP, There is a issue that is coming and please\ncheck on this. So they will check with their ISP or they will check to their own system , own firewall, \nif I am able to cross my part which means we are getting issue in other company system or IP.\nSo we have to make sure where the issue is.\n    If we will see packet structure, developer has played game over here, what they started doing is \nthat they start noticing the packet and in packet there are multiple thing which are of different use.\n        version -> tells us version of IP address. Are we using IPV6 or IPV4.\n        headers length -> it tells us the length of header from version to options.\n        total length -> it tells us total length from version to data everything. Along with the\n                data packets and everything, How much is my total length of packet\n        data part -> it is the data that we are trying to send.\n        source ip -> we already discussed\n        destination ip -> we already discussed.\n        checksum -> it make sure that, the data we are sending is not altered in the way. if anything\n                change then our checksum and data will not match. it makes sure data reached\n                to the destination without any touch ups in between.\n                there is on very interesting part of packet which is called as TTL\n\n        TTL(Time to Live) -> It is basically added in a packet to make sure there are no network \n                    loops or data is not stuck in network forever.\n                What are Network loops -> to understand network loops",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
